Beyond sight

Exploring the Impact of a Multifaceted Intervention on Knowledge, Attitudes and Behaviors towards Persons with Visual Impairment

Motivation

Social Inclusion at school

Persons with disabilities face much higher risks of poverty and social exclusion

  • In ECON a lot of the focus is placed on labor market policies
    • e.g.Â employment quotas, wage subsidies etc. (KrekÃ³ and Telegdy 2022)
  • Discrimination however is systemic and starts earlier in life with the educational system

Over the past 50 years most EU countries either abolished or reduced to a great extent special schools

  • However, being placed in an integrated classrooms does not suffice (Lindsay and Edwards 2013)
    • Negative attitudes, limited acceptance and peer social interaction (Nabors and Keyes 1997; Martinez and Carspecken 2007; Tavares 2011)
    • Teachers often lack the training to foster inclusive classroom environments and may themselves have limited awareness and biased attitudes (Garrote et al. 2020; Ginevra et al. 2022)

Can external interventions support schools to create more inclusive environments?

This paper in a nutshell

Evaluate the impact of a multifaceted intervention on a wide range of âsocial-inclusionâ outcomes in the context of visual impairment

  • Multifaceted intervenion
    • Information provision
    • Simulation | Perspective-taking exercise
    • Integroup-contact
  • Outcomes
    • Skills - knowledge of visual impairment and perspective-taking & empathic concerns
    • Attitudes - explicit (self-reported) and implicit (IAT)
    • Incentivized beliefs and social preferences (willingness to interact socially and altruism)
  • Results
    • Large positive effects on skills
    • Mixed effects on attitudes
    • No effects on any of the incentivized measures

Contributions

  • Disability Inclusion interventions in the school setting (Lindsay and Edwards 2013)
    • one of the few papers addressing visual impairment and looking beyond knowledge and explicit attitudes
  • Generally, to field and lab-in-the-field experiments on discrimination (see Bertrand and Duflo 2017 for a review; Alesina et al. 2024)

Through the intervention:

  • Information provision (Haaland, Roth, and Wohlfart 2023)
  • Empathic concerns and perspective taking for prejudice reduction and cooperation (Batson et al. 1997; Galinsky and Moskowitz 2000; Galinsky and Ku 2004; Simonovits, Kezdi, and Kardos 2018; Kardos, Kezdi, and Simonovits 2018; Alan et al. 2021)
  • Literature on intergroup contact (Allport 1954; Pettigrew and Tropp 2005; Paluck, Green, and Green 2019; Bursztyn et al. 2021)

Program and Evaluation Design

Intervention

  • Implemented in 3 upper secondary schools in Trento, North Italy (344 students)
    • Academic, technical and vocational tracks
    • 6 classes per school, two eligibility criteria
    • Delivered by a local NGO

Information treatment

1h class activity on:

  • types of visual impairment
  • strategies and tools for autonomy
  • professions and activities that can be done in autonomy
  • appropriate conduct during a social interaction
  • what it is to live with a disability, acknowledging the challenges and adaptations

Perspective taking and Inter-group contact treatment

Evaluation design and Data

Experimental Design

  • Hybrid between and within class design
    • Between - 6 classes (2 per school) serve as "pure control classes" (N = 119)
    • Within - 12 "main classes" with randomization at individual level (N = 225)
    • Why? Increase power while providing some evidence on within class spillovers

  • Waitlist design

  • Phased-in design - everyone is eventually treated

Data

  • Baseline | Endline => 2-3 weeks before | after treatment
  • Sample characteristics at baseline:
    • Avg. Age 18; 52% females
    • Roughly 80% report no contact with persons with visual disabilities
    • 86% report speaking Italian at home
    • Good balance by treatment
  • 11% attrition at endline, balanced by treatment

Empirical strategy

Regression Specification1

\[ Y_{it+1} = \gamma Di + Y_{it} + X_{it} \beta + \varepsilon_{it+1} \]

  • Main classes
    • \(Di = 1\) if received âInitial offerâ (IO) or âEver offerâ (EO)
    • ITT and LATE estimands
    • DREO estimator as robustness (De Chaisemartin and Behaghel 2020)
  • Main vs pure controls
    • \(Di = 1\) if never offered the treatment in âmain classesâ and 0 if in âpure control classesâ
    • Fischer exact tests

  1. Nonparametric tests for some of the outcomes

Outcomes and Results

Results

Skills

Outcomes

  • Knowledge: quiz on visual impairment
  • Perspective-taking (PT) and Empatic Concerns (EC)
    • subscales of the Interpersonal Reactivity Index (Davis 1980)

Positive effects on dimensions more closely related to the intervention

Results

Attitudes

Outcomes

  • Implicit attitudes
    • Implicit Association Test adapted for visual impairment (IAT) (Greenwald, McGhee, and Schwartz 1998)
  • General attitudes towards persons with visual disabilities (ATDP) (Yuker et al. 1970)
  • Multidimensional Attitudes based on a social vignette (MAS) (Findler, Vilchinsky, and Werner 2007)
    • 3 dimensions: affect (emotions), cognition (thoughts) and behaviors

Results

Social Preferences

Outcomes

  • Willingness to pay for social interaction (WTP)
  • Giving in the Dictator Game to an anonymous blind recipient (Giving Blind)

Additional outcomes

  • Giving towards a recipient with motor impairment (Giving motor) or a generic recipient (Giving generic)
  • Social Value Orientation (SVO) (Murphy, Ackermann, and Handgraaf 2011; Murphy and Ackermann 2014)

Beliefs

Instructions

As you probably know, in 2021, the summer Olympic and Paralympic games were organized in Tokio, Japan.

One of the competitions was the female 400m meters sprint. You can watch below the recording of the competition in the Olympics.

In the Paralympics, the competition is organized separately for types of disability.

In the Olympics games, participants had an average time of 47 seconds in the competition.

Guess the average time of participants with visual impairment in the Paralympcs game!

Other games:

  • performance in a memory test
  • performance in a math test (summation and multiplication)
  • reported life-satisfaction in a representative survey

Results

Beliefs

Potential Concerns

Social Desirability and Spillovers

Social Desirability

  • Propensity to give socially desireble answers measured at endline (Crowne and Marlowe 1960; Manganelli, Canova, and Marcorin 2000)
    • Positive ES of 0.09 (p-value = 0.53)
    • Including it as endogenous control reduces ESs by 10-20%

Spillovers

Conclusion

  • Main Findings

    • \((+)\) effects on knowledge and empathic concerns
    • \((+)\) effects on generalized attitudes
    • at best no impact on implicit attitudes
    • no impact on willingness to interact socially or expected emotions, thoughts and behaviors in the context of a social interaction
    • no impact on beliefs or altruism

  • Main contribution: assessing impacts only on knowledge and self-reported attitudes may not paint the full picuture in terms of inclusion?

  • Limitations

    • sample size and external validity
    • one shot intervention
    • no measure of actual behaviors
